The Nigerian Bar Association (NBA) has reduced the registration fee that participants will pay for its 2022 Annual General Conference (AGC). The registration started on June 12. Senior Advocates of Nigeria (SANs), Attorneys General, and Benchers will pay N190,000 under early bird registration for the AGC holding in Lagos in August. The Technical Committee on Conference Planning (TCCP) for the 2022 AGC announced this in a statement. The conference, which is scheduled to hold at the Eko Atlantic City, Victoria Island, Lagos, from August 19 to 26, has the theme: Bold Transitions. Renowned Nigerian author, Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie, will be the keynote speaker. Technical Committee on Conference Planning (TCCP) Chairman Tobenna Erojikwe said registration for the conference opened on June 12 with an early bird registration window. He added that participants would be able to register for either physical attendance or virtual attendance at www.nbaconference.com. According to the TCCP statement, early bird registration for the conference will run till June 17, while regular registration will start on July 18 and end on August 5. Late registration will run between August 6 and 12, 2022, while registration for virtual attendance will be continuous. The registration fees are broken down according to categories. There has also been a significant reduction in the fees for virtual attendance compared to what obtained in 2021.   ICRC sets January date for production of military,…     Democracy Day: Abiru preaches peace     2023: Join forces with APGA to rescue Benue, Waya pleads   Lawyers in the category of one to five years of practice will pay N15,000 for early bird registration; N40,000 for regular registration; N80,000 for late registration and N5,000 for virtual attendance, as against N7,500 charged last year. Lawyers within the six to 10 years of practice category will register with N22,000 for early bird; N60,000 for regular; N120,000 for late registration and N10,000 for virtual participation, compared to N11,250 they paid for virtual participation last year, among others. Lawyers who have practised between 11 and 15 years will pay N36,000 registration fee, if they use the early bird window; N70,000 for regular registration; N140,000 for late registration and N15,000 for virtual attendance, N3,000 less than the N18,000 they were charged last year. For lawyers having 16 to 20 years of practice, the cost is N54,000 for early bird; N80,000 for regular; N180,000 for late registration and N20,000 for virtual registration, compared to N27,000 paid in 2021. Lawyers who have more than 20 years of practice will pay N95,000, if they use the early bird window; N150,000 for regular; N300,000 for late registration and N30,000 for virtual attendance, a difference of N17,500 reduction from what it cost them in 2021. Senior Advocates of Nigeria (SANs), Attorneys General, and Benchers will pay N190,000 for early bird; N300,000 for regular; N500,000 for late registration and N50,000 for virtual participation, showing N45,000 less than the N95,000 they paid last year. It will cost Magistrates and other Judicial Officers N50,000 to register, if they use the early bird window; N50,000 for regular; N50,000 for late registration and N20,000 for virtual attendance, compared to N25,000 they paid last year. Justices, Judges, Grand Khadis and Khadis will pay N75,000 registration, whether they use the early bird window or not, regular registration or late registration. But if they wish to participate virtually, the cost is N25,000, instead of N37,500 they paid in 2021. For non-lawyers who want to attend the conference, the fee is N100,000, irrespective of whether it is early bird, regular or late registration. If they want to register to attend virtually, the fee is N30,000; N20,000 less than last year’s fee. International delegates will pay $300 for either early bird, regular or late registration, but $100 for virtual attendance, $50 less than last year’s fee. “The AGC will bring together thought leaders in the areas of justice delivery, technology, economy, politics, judicial reforms, human rights, and rule of law. “The aim is to have leading lawyers and thought leaders in the various fields to discuss and harmonise positions on the way forward on building a more effective Bar and a resilient country able to thrive amidst changing global dynamics,” Erojikwe said.